===message:Good point Robert. Unlike wars of the past, modern wars are not about ideological, political, or economic issues, they are cultural. Post-Cold War politics is now the interaction of Western power and culture with the culture and power of non-Western civilizations such as Confucian and Islamic societies. It is one of Western universalism and Muslim militancy. One grim philosophy of life for this new era was well expressed by the Venetian nationalist demagogue in Michael Dibdin’s novel, Dead Lagoon: “There can be no true friends without true enemies. Unless we hate what we are not, we cannot love what we are. These are the old truths we are painfully rediscovering after a century and more of sentimental cant. Those who deny them deny their family, their heritage, their culture, their birthright, their very selves! They will not lightly be forgiven.” The unfortunate truth in this cannot be ignored. For peoples seeking identity and reinventing ethnicity, enemies are essential and the potentially most dangerous enemies occur between the world’s major civilizations. Worse yet, many of our enemies, such as fanatical, extremist Muslims, are living in our own country and are protected by our laws.


=========yorg=========
===subject:Reply to Doug's Reply
===from:Robert Jones
===date:Sun Sep  8 23:25:24 2002
===message:That is a great quote, Doug, and it is so true. It is nice to see that someone in this course has  similar historical perspectives to my own. Every era of the world’s history has been filled with wars of conquest and religion. And more times than not, the true explanation of these events stare many history enthusiasts in the face as they stumble over society’s desire for political correctness. Many, including some in this class (at least from what I’ve read in response to my postings here), dismiss war as blood and guts, guns and death. As true of a characterization as that may be on a superficial level, war has provided all of us a place to live and the right to choose our government and some sense of security against our foes. If you get a chance, take a look at some of the responses that I have received on the first three topics. Maybe I am a bit cynical at times, but I feel like views like yours and mine are being dismissed merely because they discuss war and society on a deeper level and may sound threatening to the mainstream, politically correct school of thought. What do you think?  
