===subject:Episode 4
===from:Keith Lewis
===date:Tue Oct  8 15:34:27 2002
===message:In All Quiet On The Western Front, the soilders humorously discussed the reasons for war.  These underlying basic reasons were similar to a school-yard fist fight.  The men explain that war is the result of two country's having an argument, and the example of one people disliking another.  Since the soilder's did not have any prolem with anyone, he wanted to go home.  This makes good satire, but is tremendously unrealistic.  After the events of the Twentieth Century have taught world leaders (those who believe in the repetition of history, anyway)that isolationsim is not a workable policy for preventing war.  Which, the United States almost learned the hard way in both World War I and World War II.  As if government leaders had not learned from the previous generation's mistakes, they continued to ignore the war until it became a clear and present threat to us.  
    Wars happen for many reasons, but more often are set up by leaders seeking their own agendas.  For example, the French fear and dislike of the Germans after World War I prompted French delegates to persuade the League of Nations to place tremendous reparations on the Germans for the War, admit that the Germans were solely responsible for the War (even though history proves this wrong), and sets up Germany's resolve to rise to revenge in Europe.  World War II was a direct result of the French fear of German invasion.  France seized the oppurtunity, during the League of Nations debates to disarm Germany, thereby removing that fear.
    This is one of the main problems with negotiating issues among world leaders.  Too often, issues cannot be fairly resolved because of extreme nationalism above the purpose of the organization of countries.  This became apparent in the first test of the League of Nations when Mussolini invaded Ethiopia in search of colonization.  The leader of Ethiopia pleads for the League of Nations involvement but is denied.  This was exactly the type of circumstance for which the League was created.  
     Negotiations are important to prevent large scale wars based on misunderstanding, but much improvement will have to be made within these organizations to truely foster change.  Even today, the UN either doesn't have enough power, or enough concern to hold up the agreement with Iraq.  The ideas are in place to prevent future wars, but much more work will have to be done before the world can practice total and successful pascifism.   
=========yorg=========
